 for bestpractices and # Content Calendar Prompt for AI Development Tool

This prompt is designed to guide an AI development tool to build a robust, production-ready Content Calendar feature within the LifeOps system. It covers the page, components, frontend/backend/integration requirements, UX flows, data models, security, validation, acceptance criteria, and UI/UX guidelines, all aligned with the project context and strict runtime safety rules.

---

## Content Calendar

### Overview
Build a calendar-based scheduling UI for content items that supports publishing slots, drag-to-schedule, and conflict detection. This page sits at the nexus of Content Pipeline Automation (idea → research → drafting → editing → scheduling → publishing with LLM-assisted workflows and publishing connectors) and the Content Editor workflow (end-to-end editor with collaboration, versioning, and publishing integrations). The UI must be fast, keyboard-friendly, accessible, and highly responsive, with a dark, dense, power-user aesthetic consistent with LifeOps design language.

---

## Page Description (Full Detail)

What this page is:
- A central Content Calendar that visualizes content items across time (month/week/day views) and channels, enabling drag-and-drop scheduling of publish slots, rescheduling, and conflict detection (team capacity, slot overlaps, channel restrictions).

Goals:
- Provide an at-a-glance calendar with scalable views (Month, Week, Day) that render content cards as scheduled items.
- Support drag-and-drop of content cards between slots, days, or channels, with live conflict detection and automated suggestions.
- Show a Conflicts Panel listing overlapping slots, capacity warnings, and actionable next steps.
- Include a Quick Create flow to rapidly add a content card with essential metadata (title, type, target channel, tentative publish window).
- Connect with Content Pipeline Automation to automatically seed ideas, research tasks, drafts, edits, and scheduling where appropriate.
- Integrate with the Content Editor for deeper editing, versioning, and publishing connectors.
- Ensure all actions are logged, reversible, and traceable with an audit trail.

UI elements and how they need to look:
- Month/Week/Day Views: horizontally laid-out timeline with days/weeks and vertical lanes per publishing channel or team.
- Drag & Drop Scheduling: draggable content cards that snap to slots; when dragged over a slot, show live slot feasibility and conflict indicators.
- Conflicts Panel: side panel listing conflicts with severity badges, suggested resolutions, and one-click actions (reschedule, reassign, escalate).
- Quick Create: modal or in-view inline form to create content items with minimal metadata, auto-populating from templates when possible.
- Visual guidance: high-contrast white typography on near-black background; subtle card elevation, gradient card backs, and accent pills for statuses.

Connected Pages:
- Content Editor: Full workflow from ideation to publish with LLM-assisted writing, versioning, and publishing integrations.
- Content Pipeline Automation: End-to-end automation spanning ideation → research → drafting → editing → scheduling → publishing with LLM assistance and publishing connectors.

UI guidance and constraints:
- Dense, keyboard-navigable, accessible controls.
- Drag-and-drop must be robust with proper aria attributes and keyboard equivalents.
- Conflicts should be detectable in real time with clear visual indicators and accessible messaging.

---

## Components to Build

1. CalendarView (Main Page)
   - Props: timeRange (Month/Week/Day), channels[], items[], viewDate
   - State: selectedSlot, draggingItem, viewMode, filters
   - Features: render calendar grid, render content cards, drag-and-drop support, conflict detection overlays, responsive layout
   - Data handling: consume sanitized items via API; ensure data ?? [] usage; guard array operations

2. ContentCard
   - Props: item { id, title, type, status, channel, publishAt, duration, assignees, priority, metadata }
   - UI: icon/thumbnail, title, channel badge, publish time, status pill, assignees
   - Interactions: click to open in Content Editor, drag handle, quick actions (reschedule, reassign)

3. ChannelLane
   - Props: channel, items[]
   - UI: vertical lane for each channel, slot grid within lane
   - Features: drop target for ContentCard, slot locking/availability states

4. ConflictsPanel
   - Props: conflicts[] (each with type: overlap, capacity, channel, items[])
   - UI: list with severity badges, concise details, actions (suggested reschedule, reassign, approve)
   - Behavior: filterable by severity, prioritized stacking, accessible via keyboard

5. QuickCreateModal
   - Props: onCreate
   - Fields: title, type, channel, tentativePublishAt, duration
   - Validation: required fields, sensible defaults, auto-suggestion for templates

6. Drag-and-Drop Engine
   - Libraries: react-dnd or native pointer-based system with accessible fallbacks
   - Requirements: snapshot of drag state, collision detection with slots, live feedback

7. ConflictDetector
   - Inputs: items, slots, channelCapacity
   - Outputs: conflicts list with reason codes (overlap, capacity, tool restriction)
   - Real-time updates as item positions change

8. API Bridge (Frontend Services)
   - fetchCalendarItems(query): GET calendar items within range
   - createCalendarItem(payload): POST new item
   - updateCalendarItem(id, payload): PATCH/PUT
   - bulkReschedule(ids, newSlot): POST
   - fetchChannelCapacity(): GET capacity per channel and time slot
   - logAudit(action, details): POST audit trail

9. AuditTrail & RunArtifactsPanel
   - Show per-action logs, diffs, and artifacts related to scheduling actions

10. Tooltip/Popovers
    - Contextual hints for drag targets, conflicts, and quick actions

---

## Implementation Requirements

### Frontend

- Architecture:
  - Component-driven with clear separation: CalendarView composed of ChannelLane, ContentCard, ConflictsPanel, and QuickCreateModal.
  - State management: local UI state for drag/drop, plus global state for calendar data via a lightweight store (e.g., React Context or Zustand) to facilitate cross-component updates.
  - Data safety: use data ?? [] for any API results; verify Array.isArray(results) before mapping; default useState<Type[]>([]) for array states.

- UI/UX:
  - Implement Month/Week/Day views with responsive breakpoints. Ensure layout gracefully degrades to a stacked vertical list on narrow viewports.
  - Drag-and-drop: smooth drag visuals, snap to grid, and live conflict feedback. Ensure keyboard alternative: arrow keys to nudge, Enter to drop.
  - Conflict indicators: inline indicators on slots and a dedicated ConflictsPanel with searchable/sortable conflicts by severity.
  - Quick Create: accessible modal with focus trapping; form validation and inline hints.

- Accessibility:
  - ARIA roles for calendar regions, drag-and-drop, and modal dialogs.
  - Keyboard focus management during drag, drop, and modal open.
  - Color contrast checks comply with WCAG AA for text on backgrounds.

- Performance:
  - Virtualization for large calendars (only render visible rows/slots).
  - Debounce rapid updates; batch API calls for consecutive edits.
  - Efficient re-renders: use memoization where appropriate.

- Runtime Safety:
  - All API results accessed with nullish coalescing and guards:
    - const items = data ?? [];
    - Array.isArray(items) ? items.map(...) : []
  - Initialize React state with correct types:
    - const [items, setItems] = useState<Item[]>([]);
  - Access nested API responses with optional chaining:
    - response?.data?.items ?? []
  - Destructure with defaults:
    - const { items = [], conflicts = [] } = response ?? {};

- Data flows:
  - On load: fetchCalendarItems for the visible range; render items per channel lane.
  - On drag: compute potential drop slot; if conflict detected, show warning and disable drop if critical.
  - On drop/confirm: call updateCalendarItem or createCalendarItem; push audit trail entry.
  - When a conflict is detected, update ConflictsPanel in real-time.

### Backend

- Data models (schemata):
  - ContentItem
    - id: string
    - title: string
    - type: string (ideation, research, draft, edit, schedule, publish)
    - channelId: string
    - publishAt: string (ISO datetime)
    - durationMinutes: number
    - status: string (planned, in-progress, published, blocked)
    - assignees: string[]
    - version: number
    - metadata: object
    - createdAt: string
    - updatedAt: string
  - Channel
    - id: string
    - name: string
    - capacityPerSlot: number
    - color: string
  - Conflict
    - id: string
    - channelId: string
    - slotStart: string
    - slotEnd: string
    - reason: string
    - severity: string (low|medium|high)
    - itemIds: string[]
  - AuditLog
    - id: string
    - action: string
    - actorId: string
    - targetItemId: string
    - details: string
    - createdAt: string

- API endpoints:
  - GET /api/calendar/items?start=...&end=...&channels=...
    - Returns: { data: ContentItem[], meta: { total } }
  - POST /api/calendar/items
    - Body: { title, type, channelId, publishAt, durationMinutes, assignees, metadata }
    - Returns: Created ContentItem
  - PATCH /api/calendar/items/{id}
    - Body: partial ContentItem fields to update
  - POST /api/calendar/items/bulk-reschedule
    - Body: { itemIds: string[], newPublishAt: string, newChannelId?: string }
  - GET /api/channels
    - Returns: Channel[]
  - GET /api/channels/capacity
    - Returns: { [channelId]: capacityPerSlot }
  - POST /api/audit
    - Body: { action, actorId, targetItemId, details }

- Business logic:
  - Conflict detection: two or more items overlapping on the same channel/time with capacity constraints triggers a conflict.
  - Slot snapping: when dragging, snap to nearest valid slot; if none, show unavailable state.
  - Conflict resolution: suggest rescheduling to the next available slot or reassigning to another channel; allow approvals where required.

- Security:
  - Authentication: JWT-based or session-based per LifeOps auth strategy.
  - Authorization: ensure only users with scheduling rights and appropriate roles can create/update calendar items; enforce per-channel permissions.
  - Audit trails: every create/update/delete/action logged with reversible capability.

- Validation:
  - Server-side validation for required fields, types, valid channelId, and publishAt in ISO format.
  - Validate arrays (assignees) and nested metadata safely; ensure no nulls cause runtime errors.

### Integration

- Data flows:
  - Frontend fetches calendar items and channels; backend returns validated structures.
  - On scheduling actions, frontend updates are persisted via API and then reflected in UI immediately; audit logs stored for traceability.
  - Content Pipeline Automation hooks are triggered on key state transitions (e.g., idea → research → draft) as part of the broader LifeOps orchestration, with events emitted to agent orchestration layer.

- Inter-module connections:
  - Content Calendar consumes signals from Content Pipeline Automation for upcoming items and templates.
  - Content Editor integration: selecting a calendar item navigates to the Editor with preloaded item context; edits and versioning flow back to calendar state.

---

## User Experience Flow

1. User lands on Content Calendar main page.
   - See a multi-channel calendar with days/weeks/month views.
   - All items pre-populated for the visible range; channels display order and capacity indicators.

2. User switches to Week or Day view for granular scheduling.
   - Cards appear in their respective channel lanes with clear time blocks.
   - Slot grid indicates available publishing slots.

3. User drags a ContentCard to a new time slot or channel.
   - Live drag feedback shows potential drop target.
   - If the target slot is valid and within capacity, the card snaps and a subtle confirmation appears.
   - If the target creates a conflict, a warning badge appears; drop is prevented or requires a confirm.

4. User opens ConflictsPanel to review conflicts.
   - Conflicts are listed with severity and recommended actions.
   - User can choose to reschedule, reassign, or approve an automatic resolution if permitted.

5. User uses Quick Create to add a new content item.
   - Minimal metadata form; upon submit, item appears in the calendar at the current view location or a chosen default slot.

6. User clicks a calendar item to open the Content Editor workflow.
   - Opens the Editor with idea → research → draft → edit → schedule → publish workflow steps.
   - User can edit content, trigger LLM-assisted writing, manage versions, and connect to publishing connectors.

7. System logs audit trails for every action.
   - Users can review run artifacts and diffs in AuditTrail panels.

8. All actions are reversible where possible.
   - Users can revert scheduling changes to previous states; audit logs store diffs.

---

