- Authentication: token/session-based per LifeOps standard (JWT recommended for stateless APIs)
- Authorization: per-channel permissions for create/update; enforce safety rails and approvals where applicable
- Data validation and sanitization on server for all inputs
- Audit trail preserved for all scheduling actions

### Validation Rules
- Required: title, channelId, publishAt for create; channelId exists and is valid
- publishAt must be ISO 8601
- durationMinutes > 0
- assignees must be an array of strings
- Optional nested metadata must be sanitized
- All API responses guarded with data ?? [] prior to mapping or iteration

---

## Acceptance Criteria

- [ ] The Content Calendar renders correctly in Month, Week, and Day views with all channels and items for the visible date range.
- [ ] Drag-and-drop scheduling updates publishAt and channelId with real-time conflict detection; conflicts panel updates instantly.
- [ ] Quick Create creates a ContentItem with minimal metadata and appears in the correct slot, with server-side validation and audit logging.
- [ ] ConflictsPanel surfaces all overlaps and capacity issues, with actionable resolution paths (reschedule/reassign/approve).
- [ ] Opening a calendar item navigates to Content Editor with the item context and supports the full idea→publish workflow.
- [ ] All API responses are validated defensively (data ?? [], Array.isArray checks) and all arrays initialized with useState([]).
- [ ] Comprehensive unit and integration tests cover: calendar rendering, drag/drop, conflict detection, API routes, and audit logs.
- [ ] Accessibility checks pass (ARIA roles, keyboard navigation, focus management in modals and drag/drop).

---

## UI/UX Guidelines

Apply the LifeOps design system precisely.

- Color palette and typography:
  - Primary background #0B0B0C, secondary #151718, panel outlines #1F1F20
  - Text: #FFFFFF; secondary meta #9DA3A6; disabled #56595B
  - Accent: #FF3B30 for active/alerts
  - Charts: teal #00C2A8, amber #FFB020, purple #8B5CF6
  - Gradients: #111213 → #1A1A1B for depth

- Typography and layout:
  - Font: Inter, SF Pro Display, or Roboto
  - Headings 600–700 weight, 20–28px; titles 14–16px; body 12–14px; captions 11–12px
  - 8px baseline grid; gutters 220–260px; header height 56–64px
  - Card radii 8–12px; shadows; borders subtle

- Card design:
  - Dark elevated cards with top inner highlight, rounded corners
  - Icon/thumbnail at top, then title, then metadata
  - Hover: translateY(-2px), border tint to #2A2A2B

- Navigation:
  - Left sidebar with icons; active state uses vertical accent pill #FF3B30
  - Collapsible sections with carets; selection uses rounded background

- Data visualization:
  - Minimal grids, low-contrast axes, colored lines with rounded caps
  - Tooltips: dark panels with white text, 8–10px radius

- Interactions:
  - Buttons: Primary, Secondary; hover lift; destructive actions emphasized
  - Form elements: dark inputs, subtle borders, focused ring in accent color
  - Toggles/chips/pills: rounded; active state uses accent
  - Micro-interactions: 120–200ms transitions; clear affordances for actions

- Design philosophy:
  - Dense, screen-focused UI for power users; high readability with restrained accent usage
  - Clear auditability and reversibility; traceable agent actions and run artifacts

---

## Mandatory Coding Standards — Runtime Safety

CRITICAL: Enforce in ALL generated code.

1. Supabase-like results handling:
   - const items = data ?? []
2. Array method safety:
   - (items ?? []).map(...)
   - Array.isArray(items) ? items.map(...) : []
3. React useState initialization for arrays:
   - const [items, setItems] = useState<Item[]>([])
4. API response validation:
   - const list = Array.isArray(response?.data) ? response.data : []
5. Optional chaining:
   - obj?.property?.nested
6. Destructuring with defaults:
   - const { items = [], count = 0 } = response ?? {}

